></p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>42</p></td><td><p>320</p></td><td><p><strong>363</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Statistics for 2015 will be available in June 2016.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-11T09:11:15.26Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457597/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457597/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457597/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","Roads: Devon","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many casualties were recorded in road traffic accidents in (a) Torridge and West Devon constituency and (b) Devon in each of the last three years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Mr Geoffrey Cox","Torridge and West Devon","Mr Geoffrey Cox","29598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457598","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Department for Transport regularly publishes Official Statistics on the proportion of roads where maintenance ‘should be considered’ in England. The smallest administrative area this information is published for is the local highway authority area. Devon County Council is the local highway authority for the constituency of Torridge and West Devon, but the Devon County Council area covers in whole or part 8 other constituencies.</p><p> </p><p>For Devon County Council we are providing £42.3 million this financial year (2015/16).</p><p> </p><p>Road maintenance is a matter for individual local highway authorities, such as Devon County Council, and it is for them to prioritise work according to local need.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-11T09:14:28.853Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457598/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457598/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457598/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","Roads: Torridge and West Devon","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make an assessment of the standard and level of maintenance of roads in Torridge and West Devon constituency; and what steps his Department has taken to improve the maintenance of those roads.","false","Biography information for Mr Geoffrey Cox","Torridge and West Devon","Mr Geoffrey Cox","29600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457599","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>Bus and coach passengers already have statutory rights under the services provisions of the Consumer Rights Act 2015. If the bus or coach service is not provided with reasonable care and skill or in line with certain information the transport operator has given about it then the passenger may be due compensation, including compensation for delays and cancellations.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-11T11:39:41.41Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457599/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457599/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457599/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","Bus Services: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will bring forward proposals to give bus and coach passengers statutory rights to compensation for delays in their bus or coach service.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","29613"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457600","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>The department operates two surveys to collect data on bus fares and bus punctuality. Bus fares information is collected from bus operators every quarter and bus punctuality is collected from local authorities every year, both via online surveys.</p><p> </p><p>In 2012 and 2015 the sample of operators from whom the Department collected data on bus fares was revised.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>For the 2012/13 bus punctuality data collection the following voluntary questions were added to the survey:</p><ul><li>Do you continue to collect/record data on bus patronage in your area?</li><li>If yes, can you please enter the number of passenger journeys on local bus services?</li><li>Please indicate if you are able to share figures for individual operators with DfT (solely for use in validation of figures we collect directly from operators)</li><li>If possible, please provide a contact name/email for any queries on the patronage data and any relevant notes in the box below (for example, if figures are not yet available but will be later)</li><li>The Department is also interested in learning more about the number of passengers carried on flexible or demand responsive modes of transport, including community transport. If you are able to supply any information on these for your area (such as number of passengers, nature of service) please enter brief details below</li></ul>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-11T12:04:51.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457600/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457600/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457600/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","Bus Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what changes his Department has made to the collection of data on bus fares and punctuality since 2010.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","29614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457601","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>The Bill will include powers to require the release of open data on routes, timetables, punctuality and fares, in a specified format.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-11T11:35:30.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457601/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457601/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457601/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","Bus Services: Fares","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether provisions in the Buses Bill will seek to require bus operators to publish data on fares.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","29611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457602","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>The Department for Transport publishes an index of local bus fares every quarter. The data are available in table BUS0415 at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/387116/bus0415.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/387116/bus0415.xls</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Table BUS0415b shows that in England from September 2005 to September 2010 the average real terms fare rise was 2.1% per year, and from September 2010 to September 2015 the average real terms fare rise was 1.5% per year.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-11T11:43:41.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457602/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457602/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457602/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","Bus Services: Fares","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what information his Department holds on trends in the prices of bus fares since 2010.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","29612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457603","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>The M6 link road to Heysham is a local road that has been funded by Government to complete the connection from the Heysham and Morecambe peninsula to Junction 34 of the M6. Neither the local authority nor the Department has raised the issue of trunking the road.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-11T11:00:40.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457603/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457603/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457603/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","M6","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the potential merits of trunking the new M6 link road from junction 34.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","29690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457604","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>Staffing levels are generally a matter for railway operators, as we believe that they are best placed to determine how to meet the needs of their passengers. However, the Department may consider on a case-by-case basis whether, exceptionally, to invite proposals involving driver-only or driver-controlled operation when it holds competitions for future franchises.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-11T10:41:36.243Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457604/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457604/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457604/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","Railways: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, for which future franchises his Department plans to specify driver-only operation.","true","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","29721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457605","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>No assessment has been made of the potential effect on passenger revenues of an extension of driver-only operation on services operated by Govia Thameslink Railway.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-11T09:23:47.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457605/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457605/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457605/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","Govia Thameslink Railway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effect on passenger revenues of an extension of driver-only operation on services operated by Govia Thameslink Railways Ltd.","true","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","29716"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457606","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p><strong> </strong>Staffing levels are generally a matter for railway operators, as we believe that they are best placed to determine how to meet the needs of their passengers. Therefore, no such estimate has been made.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-11T10:44:46.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457606/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457606/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457606/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of the rail network that will be driver-only operated by (a) 2020 and (b) 2025.","true","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","29722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457607","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>The safety of passengers and rail users is paramount on the railway and the Department for Transport would never do anything to put passengers at risk.</p><p>Driver-only operation is already in safe use on almost a third of rail services in Great Britain and has been for up to 30 years and we think that it can help to improve the service to passengers. By giving responsibility to the driver to operate the doors, the other staff on board the train could provide a better face-to-face service for passengers. Whilst we regulate Ticket Office opening times through the Ticketing and Settlement Agreement station staffing levels are a matter for operators, as we believe that railway operators themselves are best placed to determine how to meet the needs of their passengers. However, it is important that those who need assistance to travel can rely on railway staff to provide this. Each operator is required to participate in the Passenger Assist system which allows disabled passengers to book staff assistance when they require it.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise that passengers can feel very strongly about station staffing hours and we expect all operators to take on board the views of stakeholders before taking any proposal to change such hours forward.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-11T09:31:57.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457607/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457607/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457607/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","Govia Thameslink Railway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the potential effect on passenger safety and security of (a) the extension of driver-only operation on rail services operated by Govia Thameslink Railways Ltd and (b) the closure of ticket offices serving those services.","true","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","29717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457608","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>The Department cannot provide the job titles of those people in receipt of travel expenses, car allowances or subsidised health insurance as this would lead to the individuals being identified.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-11T09:18:55.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457608/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457608/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457608/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","Department for Transport: Fringe Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 25 February 2016 to Question 26826, what the job titles are of those people in receipt of travel expenses, car allowance or subsidised health insurance.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","29728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457609","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>Representatives from Govia Thameslink Railway briefed officials at the Department for Transport on their plans to carry out a consultation on proposals to change ticket office opening hours at some stations.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-11T10:17:35.19Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457609/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457609/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457609/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","Govia Thameslink Railway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions his Department has had with Govia Thameslink Railways Ltd on closure or reduction in hours of ticket offices.","true","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","29719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457610","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>Govia Thameslink Railway have made officials aware of the intention to engage with staff and their representatives regarding future plans for Driver Only Operation on some services.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-11T10:26:32.273Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457610/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457610/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457610/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","Govia Thameslink Railway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions his Department has had with Govia Thameslink Railways Ltd on extending driver-only operation on its services.","true","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","29720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457611","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>Highways England has made no recent assessment of a proposal to extend the A601(M) to the A590.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-11T11:04:03.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457611/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457611/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457611/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","A601M: A590","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether any recent assessment has been made of proposals to extend the connection of junction 35 (A601M) Carnforth on the M6 to the A590 in Cumbria.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","29691"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457612","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>None. As this is a local road and not part of the Strategic Road Network, the assessment was carried out by Lancashire County Council. However, the scheme will certainly improve access to the Port and improve accessibility for related local businesses.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-11T11:07:18.983Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457612/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457612/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457612/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","M6","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of potential increases to the  port usage of Heysham after the new Heysham M6 link road is completed; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","29692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457613","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>Network Rail leads the long term planning process, which works with local authorities and operators to identify and consider future options for capacity improvement across the rail network as a whole. Network Rail studies are underway to consider future capacity on the West Coast Main Line, but no assessment has been made at this stage by the government. In due course, the government will consider the full range of options for capacity improvements on national rail that are identified by the industry processes. These industry options will feed into the Government’s decisions on Rail Investment Strategies for the periods 2019-2024 and beyond, taking into account the recommendations of the Hendy, Bowe and Shaw reports.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-11T11:11:11.69Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457613/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457613/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457613/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","West Coast Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the potential merits of increasing capacity on the West Coast Mainline after completion of the HS2 and related projects.","false","Biography information for David Morris","Morecambe and Lunesdale","David Morris","29693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457614","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>The potential cost savings from an extension of driver-only operation were included in Govia Thameslink Railway’s formal bid for the franchise. The Department assessed all bids for the franchise against the evaluation criteria in the Invitation to Tender which can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/245041/invitation-to-tender.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/245041/invitation-to-tender.pdf</a>.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-11T09:46:52.947Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457614/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457614/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457614/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","Govia Thameslink Railway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of potential cost savings from an extension of driver-only operation on Govia Thameslink Railways services.","true","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","29718"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457615","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-08","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA) has no plans to close the driving test centre at Birchall House, Wrexham Technology Park, Wrexham that provides car practical tests. The DVSA currently provides LGV vocational testing at our site at Llay Road, Wrexham. The DVSA is looking to move testing from this site. The site will not be closed until a suitable alternative for the delivery of LGV vocational testing in the Wrexham area has been secured.</p><p /><p /> <p> </p><p /><p />","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-08T17:26:42.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457615/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457615/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457615/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","Driving Tests: Wrexham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department plans to close the driving test centre in Wrexham.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","29772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457616","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-08","<p>Brondesbury Villas is not identified in the HS2 Phase One Environmental Statement as a construction route for the purposes of the HS2 scheme. However, the Phase One Bill does included powers to enable utility protection and diversion works to be undertaken along Brondesbury Villas associated with the construction of the proposed HS2 running tunnels. The implementation of these utility protection and diversion works may involve the occasional use of HGVs along Brondesbury Villas.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-08T17:30:04.08Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457616/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457616/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457616/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether heavy goods vehicles will use access roads in Brondesbury Villas during the construction phase of High Speed 2.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","29771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457617","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-08","<p>We do not have confirmed figures for the train operating companies for the year to date. This information is confirmed to the Department at the end of the financial year and will then be published by the Department.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-08T17:22:27.85Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457617/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457617/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457617/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","Railways: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what amounts have been paid to passengers under the Passenger's Charter and Delay/Repay schemes in 2015-16 to date by each train operating company.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","29748"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457618","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>The safety of passengers and rail users is paramount on the railway and the Department for Transport would never do anything to put passengers at risk.</p><p>This system has already been in safe use on almost a third of rail services in Great Britain for up to 30 years and can help to improve the service to passengers. Giving responsibility to the driver to operate the doors can improve operational performance and can enable other staff on board the train to provide a better face-to-face service for passengers. Staffing levels are generally a matter for railway operators, as we believe that they are best placed to determine how to meet the needs of all passengers. However, it is important that those who need assistance to travel can rely on railway staff to provide this. Each operator is required to participate in the Passenger Assist system which allows disabled passengers to book staff assistance when they require it.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-11T10:49:05.727Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457618/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457618/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457618/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the potential effects of the introduction of driver-only operation on rail services on (a) passenger safety, (b) passenger assurance, (c) women passengers, (d) disabled passengers, (e) revenue protection and (f) passenger assistance.","true","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","29723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457619","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-14","<p>The public consultation closes on 15 March 2016.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-14T15:24:25.383Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457619/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457619/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457619/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","Road Traffic Offences: Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when the Government plans to conclude its consultation on changes to the fixed penalty notice and penalty points for the use of a hand-held mobile telephone whilst driving.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","29786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457620","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-14","The number of people proceeded against and the maximum fine issued for using or causing to use a mobile phone whilst driving can be viewed on the Ministry of Justice website at the following link: https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2014","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-03-14T13:26:18.793Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457620/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457620/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457620/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-03-03","Road Traffic Offences: Mobile Phones","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people were prosecuted for using a mobile telephone while driving in each year since 2010; and how many such people were subject to the maximum fine.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","29787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457621","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-11","<p>Neither the Department for Transport nor the Office of Rail and Road have held any specific discussions with Govia Thameslink Railway on changes to criteria for driver-only operation.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-03-11T10:52:46.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457621/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457621/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457621/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-03-03","Govia Thameslink Railway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions (a) his Department and (b) the Office of Rail Regulation have had with Govia Thameslink Railways Ltd on changes to criteria for driver-only operation.","true","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","29724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457622","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-08","<p>The projected increase in the number of people working as a result of the rise in State Pension age provided for by the Pensions Act 2011 was estimated to generate a significant increase in gross employment earnings. Under this new timetable the peak increase compared to the previous timetable would be £5.0 billion in 2022/23 (in 2011/12 prices).</p><p> </p><p>At an individual level, working longer and saving into a private pension will, on average, increase lifetime pension income. Taking into consideration the additional employment income, individuals’ lifetime income will be improved if they work longer. Analysis by the Institute for Fiscal Studies has shown that the rise in women’s State Pension age from 60 to 62 has been accompanied by increases in employment rates for the women affected.</p><p> </p><p>Research by the National Institute of Economic and Social Research in 2011 showed that an increase of one year in the average effective working life is estimated to result in additional annual national output worth up to one per cent of GDP. In the same research, it was estimated that real GDP would be six per cent lower than it otherwise would have been by 2030, if plans for raising the state pension age (according to the Pensions Act 2007) were not implemented.</p><p> </p><p>The increase in labour supply as a result of the Pensions Act 2011 was also estimated to boost GDP above the projected baseline of the previous timetable. GDP could be between £7 billion and £9 billion higher in 2022/23 (in 2011/12 prices); in the period 2016 to 2026, the increase in labour supply due to the increase in State Pension age could boost national output by £70 billion (in 2011/12 prices).</p><p> </p><p>More information on both impacts can be found in Annex A of the Pensions Act 2011 Impact Assessment at::</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pensions-act-2011-impact-assessment" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pensions-act-2011-impact-assessment</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","29739","2016-03-08T11:09:19.007Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457622/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457622/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457622/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-03","State Retirement Pensions: Age","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of increasing the state pension age on productivity.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","29740"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457623","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-08","<p>The projected increase in the number of people working as a result of the rise in State Pension age provided for by the Pensions Act 2011 was estimated to generate a significant increase in gross employment earnings. Under this new timetable the peak increase compared to the previous timetable would be £5.0 billion in 2022/23 (in 2011/12 prices).</p><p> </p><p>At an individual level, working longer and saving into a private pension will, on average, increase lifetime pension income. Taking into consideration the additional employment income, individuals’ lifetime income will be improved if they work longer. Analysis by the Institute for Fiscal Studies has shown that the rise in women’s State Pension age from 60 to 62 has been accompanied by increases in employment rates for the women affected.</p><p> </p><p>Research by the National Institute of Economic and Social Research in 2011 showed that an increase of one year in the average effective working life is estimated to result in additional annual national output worth up to one per cent of GDP. In the same research, it was estimated that real GDP would be six per cent lower than it otherwise would have been by 2030, if plans for raising the state pension age (according to the Pensions Act 2007) were not implemented.</p><p> </p><p>The increase in labour supply as a result of the Pensions Act 2011 was also estimated to boost GDP above the projected baseline of the previous timetable. GDP could be between £7 billion and £9 billion higher in 2022/23 (in 2011/12 prices); in the period 2016 to 2026, the increase in labour supply due to the increase in State Pension age could boost national output by £70 billion (in 2011/12 prices).</p><p> </p><p>More information on both impacts can be found in Annex A of the Pensions Act 2011 Impact Assessment at::</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pensions-act-2011-impact-assessment" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/pensions-act-2011-impact-assessment</a></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","29740","2016-03-08T11:09:18.943Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457623/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457623/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457623/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-03","State Retirement Pensions: Age","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of increasing the state pension age on savings.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","29739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457624","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-11","<p>The information about job titles is not held.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>DWP expenses are paid in line with the Civil Service Management Code.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-03-11T12:25:48.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457624/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457624/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457624/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-03","Department for Work and Pensions: Fringe Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 23 February 2016 to Question 26829, what the job titles are of those people in receipt of travel expenses, paid car allowances or subsidised health insurance.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","29727"
