"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457626","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-08","<p>In early 2013 the Government reset the Universal Credit Programme, and a clear plan was developed to ensure delivery. The Programme has since been delivering against that plan in a safe, steady and secure way.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-03-08T16:02:21.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457626/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457626/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457626/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-03","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, on what date he became aware that his Department would not be able to deliver the Universal Credit programme to its original deadline of the end of 2017.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","29762"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457627","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-08","<p>The information requested is not available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel","29780","2016-03-08T16:06:24.593Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457627/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457627/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457627/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-03","National Insurance: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the methodology and data sources set out in his Department's paper, Benefit claims by EEA nationals, published in November 2015, how many individuals are recorded in government computer systems who were nationals of a non-EEA member country at time of registration for a National Insurance number and are recorded as having arrived in 2004-05 using the earlier of (a) arrival date or (b) NINO registration date and have either (i) paid National Insurance contributions over the previous year, (ii) paid PAYE income tax over the previous year, (iii) registered any other form of activity in the relevant systems, including payments of other tax or tax in respect of self-employment or (iv) claimed benefits or tax credits over the previous year and these; and how many such people (A) claimed benefits or tax credits only and (B) paid NI or PAYE or self-assessment tax only in each year from 2004-05 to 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Mr David Davis","Haltemprice and Howden","Mr David Davis","29779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457628","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-08","<p>The information requested is not available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel","29779","2016-03-08T16:06:24.67Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457628/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457628/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457628/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-03","National Insurance: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the methodology and data sources set out in his Department's paper, Benefit claims by EEA nationals, published in November 2015, how many individuals are recorded in government computer systems who were nationals of an EEA member country, other than the UK at time of registration for a National Insurance number and are recorded as having arrived in 2004-05 using the earlier of (a) arrival date or (b) NINO registration date and have either (i) paid National Insurance contributions over the previous year, (ii) paid PAYE income tax over the previous year, (iii) registered any other form of activity in the relevant systems, including payments of other tax or tax in respect of self-employment or (iv) claimed benefits or tax credits over the previous year and these; and how many such people (A) claimed benefits or tax credits only and (B) paid NI or PAYE or self-assessment tax only in each year from 2004-05 to 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Mr David Davis","Haltemprice and Howden","Mr David Davis","29780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457629","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-03-10","<p>The Government has incurred approximately £387,155 to date on legal costs associated with judicial review challenges to the under-occupancy penalty.</p><p> </p><p>It should be noted that this figure includes VAT where this is payable (e.g. on Counsel’s fees) and disbursements but does not include costs attributable to the time spent by Government advisory lawyers, as time spent by such advisory lawyers is not recorded in a manner that allows it to be attributed to individual cases. This figure does not include all of Counsel’s fees incurred in relation to the Supreme Court hearing of MA &amp; Others/A and Rutherford v the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions (29 February to 2 March) which have not yet been billed.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-03-10T17:24:13.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457629/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457629/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457629/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-03-03","Department for Work and Pensions: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much his Department has spent on legal costs related to the under-occupancy penalty.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","29705"
