"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456828","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-09","<p>We remain concerned that a number of Chinese lawyers and human rights defenders, such as Zhang Kai, have been arrested, detained, or have simply disappeared since last July. We have raised the cases regularly with the Chinese authorities. In January, the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), raised our concerns directly with Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi in Beijing. We supported a public statement by the Delegation of the EU in Beijing on 29 January, expressing concerns about the human rights situation in China, which included the detention of lawyers.</p><p>We urge the Chinese authorities to release the detained lawyers, including Zhang Kai, and ensure all detainees have access to legal counsel of their choice.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-03-09T14:13:36.88Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456828/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456828/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456828/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-02","Zhang Kai","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the televised public confession of Kai Zhang prior to formal arrest, indictment or trial; what assessment they have made of what legal assistance he is receiving and what contact he has been permitted to have with his family; what contact the UK authorities have had with him; and what representations they have made to the government of China on his behalf.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456829","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-14","<p>We pay close attention to the human rights situation in China and regularly raise our concerns about freedom of religion and the restrictions placed on Christianity. We make representations on specific cases during the annual UK-China Human Rights Dialogue. The next Dialogue is scheduled for April 2016. We also raise our public concerns about freedom of religion and belief in China in the Foreign and Commonwealth Office’s Annual Report on Human Rights and Democracy.</p><p>Regarding the recent trial of Christian leaders in Zhejiang, we remain concerned about the application of due legal process and transparency of justice in China. We are particularly concerned that people seeking to peacefully exercise their right to freedom of expression or belief are being prevented from doing so. We urge China to protect civil and political rights in line with its constitution and international human rights commitments.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-03-14T12:23:46.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456829/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456829/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456829/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-02","China: Religious Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made on behalf of the 12 Christian leaders tried in Zhejiang Province of China in February and what assessment they have made of (1) the impact of that trial and the sentences handed down on the right to freedom of religion or belief in China, and (2) how those events have been received in China.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6643"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456830","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-15","<p>We are concerned about the treatment of refugees and asylum seekers in Thailand. Thailand is not a signatory to the 1951 UN Convention on Refugees. Once any form of legal immigration status expires, refugees and asylum claimants can be deemed illegally in the country even if they have registered with the UN High Commissioner for Refugees. Nonetheless, we have pressed the Thai authorities to apply international humanitarian norms and standards when handling these vulnerable groups. We are also working with the Thai authorities to improve conditions of detention.</p>",,"Earl of Courtown",,"2016-03-15T16:26:48.527Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456830/answer","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456830/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456830/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-02","Thailand: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of (1) the conditions faced by Pakistani refugees who have been incarcerated in detention centres in Thailand, and (2) the allegations contained in the BBC World documentary <i>Our World</i>, broadcast on 27 February, that women and children are being held there, despite being UN-registered asylum seekers; and when they last discussed that situation with the UNHCR and the government of Thailand.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456831","Department of Health","false","2016-03-14","<p>NHS England is currently auditing prison screening for learning disabilities, but this information is not collected centrally at present.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-03-14T15:13:33.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456831/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456831/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456831/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-02","Prisoners: Learning Disability","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many individual prisoner screening assessments for learning disabilities were undertaken in each prison in England in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradley",,"Lord Bradley","HL6645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456832","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-10","<p>The Government has regular discussions with EU and non-EU partners on refugees and migration. The Government’s consistent focus is on securing a durable and comprehensive solution to the current migration crisis, which tackles the causes of migration as well as the consequences. The UK-France Summit Communiqué contains information on our bilateral cooperation in this area. The Government will report the details of all relevant meetings to Parliament as appropriate.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-03-10T15:39:23.69Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456832/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456832/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456832/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-02","EU Immigration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress as regards refugees and migrants they are seeking from the planned France–UK, internal EU, EU–Turkey and UNHCR meetings; and whether they will report to Parliament on the results of those meetings.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL6646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456833","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-03-11","<p>I refer the noble Lord to the statement I made to this House on Monday 7 March (Official Report, column 1079). The Royal Navy has deployed Royal Fleet Auxiliary (RFA) Mounts Bay and a Wildcat helicopter to support NATO activity in the Aegean Sea. These will work alongside three Home Office vessels: VOS Grace, which has been deployed since November; the cutter Protector, which is en route to the region; and a further cutter that is expected to start operations later this month.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to RFA Mounts Bay, there are five NATO ships on station at the moment. Canada, Germany, Greece, Italy, and Turkey have each deployed a ship.</p><p> </p><p>NATO ships will provide information to enable Greek and Turkish civilian authorities to intercept migrant vessels and arrest traffickers. It is not an interdiction or search and rescue operation, but RFA Mounts Bay would give assistance to any vessel it found in distress, in accordance with international obligations.</p><p> </p><p>With regards to sufficiency, we note the substantial contribution being made by the UK and other members of NATO, but we always look to see what further contributions members of the Alliance can make.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL6744","2016-03-11T13:50:30.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456833/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456833/answer","Hansard Extract 7 March 2016.docx","Refugees and Migrants","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456833/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-03-02","Aegean Sea: Human Trafficking","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have plans to reinforce the Royal Navy's operations in the Aegean Sea in order to save more lives and to arrest more traffickers.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL6647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456834","Home Office","false","2016-04-12","<p>Data on cases progressed under the Dublin III Regulation is recorded on the main immigration database. However, this data is not held in a way that allows it to be reported on automatically and is therefore not currently available.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-04-12T10:49:22.143Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456834/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456834/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456834/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-02","Asylum: EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many take charge requests the UK has received from each EU country per year since Dublin III came into force; how many of those were successful; how many involved minors; and how many of those requests involving minors were successful.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jowell",,"Baroness Jowell","HL6648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456835","Home Office","false","2016-03-23","<p>The Dublin III Regulation came into force on 1 January 2014. The 3 most common reasons for the refusal of take charge requests by the UK have been Articles 6.5 and 8 (both of which relate to the legal presence of a qualified relative of the minor in another Member State) and Article12.4 (which requires the Member State to take charge following the expiry of certain residence and entry visas).</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-03-23T16:11:29.49Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456835/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456835/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456835/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-03-02","Asylum: EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what have been the most common three grounds for refusing a take charge request since Dublin III came into force.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jowell",,"Baroness Jowell","HL6649"
