nson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456917/answer/previousversion/49631","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-02","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much his Department spent on salaries for (a) senior Civil Servants and (b) all other grades at (i) St Paul's Place, Sheffield and (ii) 1 Victoria Street, London in (A) 2014-15 and (B) 2015-16 to date.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","29372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456919","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-07","<p>The Government recognises that late payment remains an important issue for small businesses in the UK and is taking significant steps to assist small businesses to recover late payment debts. This is part of a package of measures to tackle late payment. We have also legislated for new transparency measures in the private sector.</p><p>The Small Business Enterprise and Employment Act 2015 legislated for a new reporting requirement on the UK’s largest companies and Regulations which will be introduced this year. This will compel larger companies to report on payment practices and performance. This information will be published on a six-monthly basis and will be made publicly available.</p><p>Through the Enterprise Bill, currently before Parliament, we will legislate to establish a Small Business Commissioner to give general advice and to help small businesses resolve disputes relating to payment matters with larger businesses.</p><p>Tackling late payment is about creating a responsible payment culture where larger companies recognise the benefit of having a sustainable and robust supply chain, and smaller businesses feel able to challenge poor behaviour. Once implemented, the Government is confident that these measures will lead to significant changes in the UK’s payment culture.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-07T11:48:59.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456919/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456919/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456919/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-02","Business: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that companies with more than 250 employees pay their suppliers in a timely manner.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","29433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456920","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-09","<p><em>The European Commission conducts trade negotiations – including the </em>Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership<em> (TTIP) – on behalf of the EU and, where appropriate, Member States. The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills does not therefore incur the direct costs of the TTIP negotiating rounds. </em></p><p> </p><p>It is rare that travel undertaken by Ministers and officials relates solely to TTIP, but will usually encompass other issues. Officials within the Transatlantic and International Unit in my Department have the lead policy responsibility for TTIP as well as certain other international matters. The total travel expenditure by these officials in 2014/15 was £25,081, in 2015/16 £14,269.</p><p> </p><p>The cost to the Department of any travel undertaken in relation to TTIP is greatly offset by the economic prize that an ambitious agreement offers. Independent analysis shows that a comprehensive TTIP agreement could give an annual boost to the UK economy of as much as £10 billion each year.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","29561","2016-03-09T15:19:19.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456920/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456920/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456920/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456920/answer/previousversion/49582","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-02","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 2 March to Question 28299, on Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership, if he will estimate the cost to his Department of each of the 12 rounds of negotiations; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","29456"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456921","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-09","<p>The Government is fully committed to the continuing success of the automotive sector and supports the development of future car technologies through a variety of mechanisms depending on the technology and stage of development. The most significant sources of funding are set out in the following table:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>13/14</p></td><td><p>14/15</p></td><td><p>15/16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>BIS (incl. Innovate UK &amp; Advanced Propulsion Centre)</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>40.5</p></td><td><p>27.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Office for Low Emission Vehicles</p></td><td><p>17.5</p></td><td><p>8.9</p></td><td><p>10.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Connected and Autonomous Vehicles (BIS, DfT &amp; HMT)</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>15.75</p></td><td><p>23.75</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total (£M)</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>27.5</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>65.15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>61.95</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>In addition the Engineering and Physical Sciences Research Council has invested £127M in research relevant to the automotive sector since FY 13/14.</p><p>In the last Spending Review my right hon. Friend the Chancellor of the Exchequer confirmed Government funding for the Advanced Propulsion Centre out to 2023 and announced additional support for automotive R&amp;D of £225m from 2023 to 2026.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-09T11:06:47.923Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456921/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456921/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456921/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-02","Cars: Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much the Government has invested into research and development of future car technologies in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Julian Knight","Solihull","Julian Knight","29466"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456922","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-10","<p>There have been over 2.4 million apprenticeship starts over the previous parliament, and 153,100 between August and October 2015, demonstrating the continued expansion of the apprenticeships programme.</p><p>We are taking action to support and encourage the growth of apprenticeships in all sectors to meet our commitment to reaching 3 million starts by 2020. The UK-wide levy will be introduced in April 2017 for all employers in public and private sector with a pay bill of £3m or more, to help fund the increase in quantity and quality of apprenticeship training in England. All employers that hire apprentices will benefit from the levy.</p><p>Our apprenticeship reforms are giving employers the opportunity to create new apprenticeship standards. More than 1300 employers are involved with 204 new standards published (of which over 60 are Higher and Degree Apprenticeships) and more than 150 are in development. So far there have been over 1,000 starts on the new standards.</p><p>We are continuing to support small employers to hire apprentices through the Apprenticeship Grant for Employers (AGE), which provides eligible employers with a £1,500 grant per apprentice (aged 16 to 24) for up to five new apprentices currently. The AGE will continue to operate until the apprenticeships levy is introduced in April 2017. From April 2016, all employers will not be required to pay employer National Insurance contributions for apprentices under age of 25 on earnings up to the upper earnings limit.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","29468","2016-03-10T16:37:54.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456922/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456922/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456922/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-02","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what progress his Department has made in encouraging private companies to create or expand their apprenticeships programmes.","false","Biography information for David Mackintosh","Northampton South","David Mackintosh","29467"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456923","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-10","<p>There have been over 2.4 million apprenticeship starts over the previous parliament, and 153,100 between August and October 2015, demonstrating the continued expansion of the apprenticeships programme.</p><p>We are taking action to support and encourage the growth of apprenticeships in all sectors to meet our commitment to reaching 3 million starts by 2020. The UK-wide levy will be introduced in April 2017 for all employers in public and private sector with a pay bill of £3m or more, to help fund the increase in quantity and quality of apprenticeship training in England. All employers that hire apprentices will benefit from the levy.</p><p>Our apprenticeship reforms are giving employers the opportunity to create new apprenticeship standards. More than 1300 employers are involved with 204 new standards published (of which over 60 are Higher and Degree Apprenticeships) and more than 150 are in development. So far there have been over 1,000 starts on the new standards.</p><p>We are continuing to support small employers to hire apprentices through the Apprenticeship Grant for Employers (AGE), which provides eligible employers with a £1,500 grant per apprentice (aged 16 to 24) for up to five new apprentices currently. The AGE will continue to operate until the apprenticeships levy is introduced in April 2017. From April 2016, all employers will not be required to pay employer National Insurance contributions for apprentices under age of 25 on earnings up to the upper earnings limit.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","29467","2016-03-10T16:37:54.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456923/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456923/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/456923/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-03-02","Apprentices",